[[File:Trench-run.png|thumb|right|300px|[[X-wing starfighter/Legends|X-wing starfighters]] performing terrain-following flying during the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]].]]
'''Terrain-following flying''' referred to a tactic in which [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighters]] or combat [[Airspeeder/Legends|airspeeders]] would fly at altitudes that were perilously close to the surface of a [[Planet/Legends|planet]], [[Moon/Legends|moon]], or other celestial body. Often used to defy detection from varying types of [[Sensor/Legends|sensors]] while ''en route'' to or making a run in on a target, requiring superior situational awareness and reflexes in order to avoid crashing.

==Characteristics==
This type of piloting was particularly dangerous to both machine and being as the tactic was at its most effective when executed through unstable, unpredictable terrain, such as that of [[Mountain/Legends|mountain]] ranges, cityscapes, [[Asteroid/Legends|asteroids]], or the most famous instance of terrain-following flying, the [[Trench Run Defense|trench run]] phase of the [[Battle of Yavin/Legends|Battle of Yavin]].<ref name="ANH">{{Film|IV}}</ref> Due to the nature of most types of sensors used throughout [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]], flying in such close proximity to the surface of a world essentially scrambled their readings; instead of detecting a starfighter executing the tactic, they would simply return a readout of the ground itself. This was a particular flaw of so-called "line-of-sight" forms of detection.<ref name="soa">''[[X-Wing: Starfighters of Adumar]]''</ref> Similar tactics included the [[Terrain-following flying|Horizon Approach]] and [[Hull skimming]].

==History==
The tactic of flying extremely close to the surface of a world to avoid detection was, perhaps, as old as the concept of flying itself, long before the age of [[Space warfare/Legends|space warfare]] and interplanetary conquest. The most famous instances of terrain-following flying were practiced by the starfighters of the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]] and later the [[New Republic Defense Force/Legends|New Republic Defense Force]], though they were by no means the only practitioners. Those who were the victims of this tactic soon learned to adopt it themselves; such flying was best-suited for small-scale raids against outlying targets or those with a minimum of air- or space-based defenses or those that were inadequate for defending against starfighters.

During the Battle of Yavin, [[Gold Squadron (Rebel Alliance)/Legends|Gold]] and [[Red Squadron (Rebel Alliance)/Legends|Red Squadrons]] used terrain-following flying as they attempted to exploit a weakness in the design of the original [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|Death Star]]. Flying through an equatorial trench that ringed the surface of the vast battlemoon, they attempted to elude the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire's]] [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE/LN starfighters]] as well as the guns on the surface; though the trench itself was also lined with [[Turbolaser/Legends|turbolaser]] emplacements, they were too heavy and slow to effectively target the smaller [[T-65 X-wing starfighter/Legends|X-]] and [[BTL Y-wing starfighter/Legends|Y-wings]] of the Rebels. However, [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] and his [[Wingmate/Legends|wingmates]] were able to do the same thing, downing two successive attempts by the Alliance forces to fire their [[Proton torpedo/Legends|proton torpedoes]] into the [[Thermal exhaust port/Legends|thermal exhaust port]] at the end of the trench. However, [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]], utilizing his newfound powers in [[The Force/Legends|the Force]], was able to succeed in destroying the battle station.<ref name="ANH" />

[[File:MillenniumFalconHothAsteroid-MF55.png|thumb|300px|right|The ''Millennium Falcon'' used terrain-following flying to navigate the large asteroids of the Hoth asteroid field.]]
Following the victory at Yavin, the Rebels continued to utilize the tactic, adapting it for runs against Imperial [[Capital ship/Legends|capital ships]] in what came to be known as the [[Trench Run Defense]].<ref name="The Rebel Alliance Sourcebook">''[[The Rebel Alliance Sourcebook]]''</ref> The heavy firepower of the [[Star Destroyer/Legends|Star Destroyers]] that made up the bulk of the heavy units within the [[Imperial Navy/Legends|Imperial Navy]] were largely ineffective against fast-moving Rebel craft, a weakness that was exploited at the [[Battle of Endor/Legends|Battle of Endor]] against a number of [[Imperial-class Star Destroyer/Legends|''Imperial''-class Star Destroyers]] as well as the [[Star Dreadnought/Legends|Star Dreadnought]] [[Executor/Legends|''Executor'']]. Flying through the canyons that lined the surface of the massive, nineteen-kilometer long vessel, a number of X-wings and [[A-wing]]s were able to strike at the warship's [[Command tower/Legends|command tower]], whose bridge [[Deflector shield/Legends|deflector shields]] had been brought down by an earlier attack pass. An A-wing flown by [[Arvel Crynyd/Legends|Arvel Crynyd]] dealt the final blow, smashing into the bridge and sending the ship plunging into the second [[Death Star II/Legends|Death Star]].<ref name="ROTJ">{{Film|VI}}</ref> The tactic continued to be used throughout the subsequent years of the [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]], including the [[Defense of Vladet]] and the [[Second Battle of Borleias|Assault on Borleias]] [[6 ABY/Legends|two years later]],<ref name="X-Wing: Rogue Squadron">''[[X-Wing: Rogue Squadron]]''</ref> as well as the [[Adumari Civil War]] in [[13 ABY/Legends|13 ABY]].<ref name="soa" />

